    Phase Retrieval in dLux¶

    In this notebook, we will go through a simple example of phase retrieval in dLux, just recovering Zernike coefficients for an aberrated circular aperture by gradient descent.

    First, we import the necessary packages, including Jax:

    Now, we initialize the parameters: a 1m telescope, in focus, with a broadband bandpass.

    We also generate a Zernike basis, omitting the piston/tip/tilt elements, and generate some random aberrations as normally-distributed coefficients over that basis.

    As noted by Martinache et al 2013, you can only detect the sign of even-order aberrations if your pupil is not inversion-symmetric; so following that paper, we introduce a small bar asymmetry.

    In [2]:
    Copied! 
    # Basic Optical Parameters
aperture = 1.
fl = 10.     
wf_npix = 128 

# Spectral Params
min_wavel = 450e-9
max_wavel = 550e-9
wavels = np.linspace(min_wavel, max_wavel, 5)

# Zernike Parameters
basis = dl.utils.zernike_basis(11, 128, outside=0.)[3:]
coeffs = 2e-8*jr.normal(jr.PRNGKey(0), [len(basis)])

# Detector Parameters
det_npix = 512 
det_pixsize = dl.utils.nyquist_pix_airy(4, np.mean(wavels), aperture, fl)

# Generate an asymmetry
asymmetry = np.ones((wf_npix,wf_npix))
asymmetry = asymmetry.at[56:72,0:56].set(0)

    Here is the core syntax of dLux: a list of optical layers. Unlike some other systems, we are very explicit about the whole optical system: so we first initialize a wavefront, then specify its centring with a TiltWavefront layer (default is centred, but could represent an off-axis source with arguments).

    Then we pass it through a circular aperture of radius filling the whole input wavefront, and then the asymmetry: you can simply stack these and it will apply them sequentially. We then normalize the flux, and apply the Zernike aberrations with ApplyBasisOPD. The final layer is then PhysicalMFT (which maps pupil to focal planes, as opposed to AngularMFT, which maps focal to pupil planes).

    In [3]:
    Copied! 
    optical_layers = [
    dl.CreateWavefront    (wf_npix, aperture),
    dl.TiltWavefront      (),
    dl.CircularAperture   (wf_npix),
    dl.TransmissiveOptic  (asymmetry),
    dl.NormaliseWavefront (),
    dl.ApplyBasisOPD      (basis, coeffs),
    dl.PhysicalMFT        (det_npix, fl, det_pixsize)]

mask = 1.0*((optical_layers[2].array*asymmetry) > 1e-5) # for visualization, have a nan mask
mask = mask.at[mask==False].set(np.nan)
    optical_layers = [ dl.CreateWavefront (wf_npix, aperture), dl.TiltWavefront (), dl.CircularAperture (wf_npix), dl.TransmissiveOptic (asymmetry), dl.NormaliseWavefront (), dl.ApplyBasisOPD (basis, coeffs), dl.PhysicalMFT (det_npix, fl, det_pixsize)] mask = 1.0*((optical_layers[2].array*asymmetry) > 1e-5) # for visualization, have a nan mask mask = mask.at[mask==False].set(np.nan)

    Then an optical system is an equinox module which you initialize with a list of layers and a bandpass, and then the __call__ function simply generates the PSF.

    In [4]:

    osys = dl.OpticalSystem(optical_layers,wavels=wavels)
psf = osys.propagate()

aberr_in = optical_layers[5].get_total_opd()

    Now lets create a new optical system but with a new set of randomised zernikes. We do this by defining the path to the coefficients and using the .update_leaves() function to get a new optical system (called model) with the newly generated coefficient values.

    With this 'model' optical system we will see if we can learn the right ones by gradient descent

    In [5]:
    Copied! 
    # Define path to the zernikes
coeffs_path = ['layers', 5, 'coeffs']

# Generate new random set of zernikes
coeffs_init = 2e-8*jr.normal(jr.PRNGKey(1), [len(basis)])

# Generate a new model with updated zernike coefficients
model = osys.update_leaves([coeffs_path], [coeffs_init])
    # Define path to the zernikes coeffs_path = ['layers', 5, 'coeffs'] # Generate new random set of zernikes coeffs_init = 2e-8*jr.normal(jr.PRNGKey(1), [len(basis)]) # Generate a new model with updated zernike coefficients model = osys.update_leaves([coeffs_path], [coeffs_init])

    Now lets define our loss function. We can use the .get_filter_spec() function in conjunction with the path to our coefficients in order to automatically generate a filter that says we only want to get gradients for those terms!

    In [6]:
    Copied! 
    filter_spec = model.get_filter_spec([coeffs_path])
@eqx.filter_jit
@eqx.filter_value_and_grad(arg=filter_spec)
def loss_func(model, data):
    out = model.propagate()
    return -np.sum(jax.scipy.stats.poisson.logpmf(data, out))
    filter_spec = model.get_filter_spec([coeffs_path]) @eqx.filter_jit @eqx.filter_value_and_grad(arg=filter_spec) def loss_func(model, data): out = model.propagate() return -np.sum(jax.scipy.stats.poisson.logpmf(data, out))

    We can time this - even on CPU it is fast! We want to do a first call so that the loss function is jit compiled.

    Now begin the optimization loop using optax with a low learning rate.

    In [9]:
    Copied! 
    optim = optax.adam(2e-9)
opt_state = optim.init(model)

errors, grads_out, models_out = [], [], []

with tqdm(range(100),desc='Gradient Descent') as t:
    for i in t: 
        # calculate the loss and gradient
        loss, grads = loss_func(model, psf) 
        
        # apply the update
        updates, opt_state = optim.update(grads, opt_state)
        model = eqx.apply_updates(model, updates)
        
        # save results
        models_out.append(model) 
        errors.append(loss)
        grads_out.append(grads)
        
        t.set_description('Loss %.5f' % (loss)) # update the progress bar
        
final_psf = model.propagate()
    optim = optax.adam(2e-9) opt_state = optim.init(model) errors, grads_out, models_out = [], [], [] with tqdm(range(100),desc='Gradient Descent') as t: for i in t: # calculate the loss and gradient loss, grads = loss_func(model, psf) # apply the update updates, opt_state = optim.update(grads, opt_state) model = eqx.apply_updates(model, updates) # save results models_out.append(model) errors.append(loss) grads_out.append(grads) t.set_description('Loss %.5f' % (loss)) # update the progress bar final_psf = model.propagate()
